  "title": "Linearity",
  "body": "Linearity  Now that we are familiar with linear terms, we are ready for the next definition.   A differential equation is said to be linear if it only contains linear terms. That is, it can be written as If one of the terms is not linear, then the differential equation is nonlinear .   This definition may seem a bit overwhelming, but it is intended to represent all possible linear differential equations. As you will see in the examples that follow, most equations that you encounter will only have a few terms.   Determine if the following differential equation is linear.  .  To answer this question, we need either to verify that all the terms are linear or find one term that is not linear. Let's rewrite this equation like and check each term one-by-one. Since every term is linear, this differential equation is linear.    Check your Understanding  Now you Try The differential equation, , is  Linear   Yes! This DE is linear.    Non-Linear  No, Try again.    Determine if the following differential equation is linear.   Linear  Correct! Since the term is nonlinear, the DE is nonlinear.   Non-Linear  No, Try again.     "
